Hong Kong stocks closed slightly down Tuesday, narrowing down the early loss after the government announced that it has no plan to declare Hong Kong as an infected area of severe acute respiratory syndrome. The Hang Seng index dropped 37.56 point, or 0.44 percent, to close at 8,596.89, with a turnover of 8.492 billion HK dollars (1. 089 billion US dollars). The sentiment was still weak as investors were concerned about the Iraq war and the severe acute respiratory syndrome. Travel-related shares performed mixed. Cathay Pacific Airways rebounded 1.58 percent Tuesday after sharp decline in the previous trading sessions. China Southern Airlines ended flat, but China Eastern Airlines lost 1.14 percent. All the four sub-indices of Finance, Utilities, Properties and Commerce &amp; Industry decreased by 0.25 percent, 0.01 percent, 0.69 percent and 0.63 percent, respectively. China-related shares ended mixed with H shares up 0.21 percent and red chips down 0.76 percent. The technology heavy GEM Index was down 0.19 points, or 0.18 percent, to close at 108.11. Enditem 